<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="161">
Diagnosis Very close to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33688" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole crassicornis Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole crassicornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassicornis">crassicornis</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs in the major by its generally abundant pilosity, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33716" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diversipilosa">diversipilosa</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs in the longer pilosity on the first gastral tergite and abundant hairs on the waist and occiput. Also resembles 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole porcula Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole porcula Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porcula">porcula</taxonomicName>
in various traits as depicted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="161">Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 1.34, HL 1.36, SL 0.72, EL 0.20, PW 0.66. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.66, HL 0.74, SL 0.74, EL 0.14, PW 0.44. Color Major and minor: concolorous light to dark reddish brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="161">Range Known from St. Louis Co., Missouri; Ouachita Mts., Montgomery Co., Arkansas; central and western Texas; and the mountains of southern Arizona at 1280-1580 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="161">
Biology In the Ouachita Mts. of Arkansas, Stefan Cover (unpublished field notes) found colonies at three localities in open areas of mixed pine-hardwood forest, nesting beneath rocks. At the Pedernales Falls State Park, Blanco Co., Texas, he found two colonies under rocks in grassy clearings, nesting in sandy soil; and in Cochise Co., Arizona, Cover discovered a colony in cottonwood floodplain forest, apparently nesting in open soil. In western Texas, Moody and Francke (1982) found 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181655" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tetra Creighton" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tetra Creighton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetra">tetra</taxonomicName>
at 400-1600 m, nesting variously under stones and logs and in open soil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
